30:13.211 --> 30:15.646
we have the greatest
card magicians in the world.

30:16.280 --> 30:18.916
I can't help it.
I'm bored by cards.

30:19.651 --> 30:21.719
And this is exactly
why Penn and Teller

30:21.752 --> 30:24.588
won't expect some very strange
card magic from me.

30:24.622 --> 30:25.957
When it comes
to Penn and Teller,

30:25.990 --> 30:27.925
I think I know
what they think they know,

30:27.959 --> 30:28.960
and that means I know

30:28.992 --> 30:30.828
what they don't know,
you know?

30:30.862 --> 30:32.864
And hopefully,
that's good enough for me.

30:36.601 --> 30:39.436
- Back on the show,
this time live from Spain,

30:39.470 --> 30:42.740
give it up
for Adrian Carratala.

30:43.907 --> 30:45.242
- Hi, friends.

30:45.276 --> 30:47.377
What a pleasure
to be here again.

30:47.412 --> 30:50.013
Well, the last time
I was there, you accused me

30:50.048 --> 30:51.915
of hiding gimmicks
under my clothes,

30:51.950 --> 30:54.419
and I was forced to get naked
on the national TV.

30:55.420 --> 30:57.255
It's okay.
No hard feelings.

30:57.288 --> 30:59.723
But this time,
in order to be prudent,

30:59.757 --> 31:02.594
I'm not wearing
a jacket, sleeves...

31:05.063 --> 31:06.096
Or pants.

31:08.132 --> 31:10.167
These are the advantages
of video calls.

31:11.669 --> 31:14.404
Guys, I know that
you love card magic.

31:14.439 --> 31:15.606
- I do.

31:15.640 --> 31:16.673
- Especially Spanish
card magic.

31:16.708 --> 31:18.209
Yeah, I know.

31:18.242 --> 31:20.979
But I don't have any decks,

31:21.011 --> 31:23.181
and I can't be there with you.

31:23.213 --> 31:25.750
So Alyson, please imagine

31:25.782 --> 31:28.353
that you are holding
a blue deck of cards.

31:28.385 --> 31:31.422
- Okay.
- These cards are magical.

31:31.455 --> 31:32.957
If you throw them up
in the air,

31:32.990 --> 31:35.326
they will remain floating
in front of you.

31:35.359 --> 31:36.760
Go ahead, try it.

31:36.794 --> 31:39.797
- Okay.

31:39.830 --> 31:42.000
Totally worked.
Wow.

31:42.032 --> 31:43.902
It's amazing.

31:43.934 --> 31:45.002
- Okay.
Don't worry, guys.

31:45.036 --> 31:46.136
This is not the trick yet.

31:46.170 --> 31:47.605
[gentle guitar music]

31:47.638 --> 31:48.839
Alyson, as you can see now,

31:48.873 --> 31:51.174
this floating deck
is completely shuffled.

31:51.209 --> 31:54.979
So please separate out
the number cards on one side

31:55.012 --> 31:57.248
and all the picture cards
on the other side.

31:57.281 --> 31:59.150
Do it now with your hands.

31:59.182 --> 32:02.921
♪ ♪

32:02.953 --> 32:05.022
Great job.

32:05.056 --> 32:07.525
Then extend
just one of your hands

32:07.557 --> 32:09.160
and take all the number cards.

32:09.192 --> 32:11.828
♪ ♪

32:11.863 --> 32:13.397
Now, extend the other hand

32:13.431 --> 32:16.768
and take
all the picture cards.

32:16.800 --> 32:19.336
And without thinking too much,
throw in the air

32:19.369 --> 32:21.372
just one of the piles,
just one of them.

32:23.207 --> 32:24.642
Penn, it's your turn.

32:24.675 --> 32:27.711
Catch them in the air.

32:27.744 --> 32:28.880
Phew. You got it?

32:28.913 --> 32:31.449
- Yes.
- Good catch. Right.

32:31.481 --> 32:33.984
And Alyson, please tell him
what pile have you thrown

32:34.018 --> 32:35.720
so he can follow up
your thoughts.

32:36.421 --> 32:38.189
- The picture cards.

32:38.221 --> 32:39.523
- The picture cards.

32:39.557 --> 32:40.724
Good choice.
Thank you.

32:40.758 --> 32:42.727
Penn, now it's your turn.

32:42.759 --> 32:43.961
- Okay.

32:43.994 --> 32:45.329
- Please let
all the picture cards

32:45.363 --> 32:48.365
float in front of you
and separate them.

32:48.398 --> 32:49.968
All the red ones in one side,

32:50.000 --> 32:52.002
and all the black ones
on the other side.

32:52.036 --> 32:54.771
Do it now.

32:54.806 --> 32:56.140
You look great from here.

32:58.442 --> 32:59.876
And just as Alyson did it,

32:59.911 --> 33:01.813
take all the red ones
in one hand,

33:01.846 --> 33:04.082
all the black ones
in the other.

33:04.115 --> 33:06.784
Get rid of one of them
and toss to Teller

33:06.817 --> 33:08.653
the pile you want
to continue playing.

33:08.685 --> 33:11.221
Not equivoque,
it's a free choice.

33:13.724 --> 33:15.926
Great.
And tell him what pile it is

33:15.960 --> 33:17.228
so we can follow up
your thoughts.

33:17.260 --> 33:18.628
- You got the black cards.

33:18.663 --> 33:21.031
- The black ones, good choice.

33:21.065 --> 33:23.101
Teller, it's your time.

33:23.134 --> 33:25.435
Alyson and Penn have decided
to leave you

33:25.470 --> 33:27.171
the black pictures.

33:27.204 --> 33:28.972
You have to make
one last decision,

33:29.007 --> 33:30.741
the most important one.

33:30.775 --> 33:33.577
Let them float,
floating in front of you.

33:33.611 --> 33:35.947
They are all the kings,
queens, and jacks

33:35.980 --> 33:37.914
of clubs and spades.

33:37.949 --> 33:39.851
Try to visualize them.

33:39.884 --> 33:46.324
Choose the one you like,
take it, fold it into four.

33:49.093 --> 33:51.061
And this time,
at the count of three,

33:51.095 --> 33:52.430
I want you to throw it at me.

33:52.462 --> 33:54.464
Not yet,
at the count of three.

33:54.499 --> 33:57.434
One, two, three.

33:57.468 --> 34:02.773
♪ ♪

34:02.807 --> 34:04.709
Wow.

34:04.741 --> 34:06.711
What's this?

34:06.743 --> 34:09.414
Your thought has just travelled
from the USA into Spain

34:09.447 --> 34:11.648
and has become real,

34:11.681 --> 34:14.518
but know the impossibility
of this moment.

34:14.552 --> 34:17.320
this card has never been named.

34:17.355 --> 34:19.791
It's just in your mind, Teller.

34:19.824 --> 34:21.291
So for the first time,

34:21.324 --> 34:23.027
what card have you
thrown at me?

34:25.996 --> 34:28.465
- The queen of clubs.

34:28.498 --> 34:30.134
- The queen of?

34:30.168 --> 34:33.403
- Clubs.
- Let me check.

34:33.438 --> 34:36.974
Just like this queen of clubs?

34:37.007 --> 34:38.576
- Whoa!

34:42.547 --> 34:47.918
Thank you so much.

34:47.952 --> 34:48.985
Thank you.

34:50.987 --> 34:53.458
- When you're performing,
it feels like laughter

34:53.490 --> 34:55.492
is always about
to bubble out of you.

34:55.525 --> 34:57.394
Is that what
you're like on stage?

34:57.427 --> 34:59.130
- Yeah. Yeah.

34:59.163 --> 35:01.498
I tried many times
to make--to--

35:01.532 --> 35:05.402
to play serious magic,
but it don't work for me.

35:05.436 --> 35:08.106
Everybody is laughing
at me every time.

35:08.139 --> 35:11.108
- Yeah, well, it's hard to do
serious magic in boxer shorts.

35:12.809 --> 35:15.213
- It's more difficult. Yes.

35:15.246 --> 35:17.614
- What would it mean to you
to fool them tonight?

35:17.648 --> 35:21.853
- Well, it could be
a dream come true

35:21.885 --> 35:24.222
because the last time--
the week I spent with them

35:24.255 --> 35:25.655
on Las Vegas

35:25.690 --> 35:28.059
was a highlight on my career.

35:29.494 --> 35:32.996
- All right, Adrian, you made
a card appear in your hand.

35:33.030 --> 35:35.333
Let's see if you can make
a trophy appear too.

35:36.766 --> 35:38.001
- I hope.
- Hey, Adrian.

35:38.034 --> 35:40.871
There are--there are
so many different ways

35:40.905 --> 35:42.739
I could open this discussion
with you.

35:42.773 --> 35:44.608
You know, we've talked
to you back stage,

35:44.641 --> 35:45.976
we've worked
on tricks with you.

35:46.010 --> 35:48.411
When I wanted to fool Teller,
you're one of the people

35:48.445 --> 35:51.282
I went to to try to find out
a trick that would fool him.

35:51.315 --> 35:54.652
So we could not have
more respect for your ability

35:54.684 --> 35:56.820
as an inventor
and as a performer.

35:56.853 --> 35:58.489
You're just--you're
just wonderful.

35:58.523 --> 36:00.023
And this thing--

36:00.023 --> 36:02.760
it's really what
real magic would look like.

36:02.793 --> 36:04.427
You'd get a card in your head,

36:04.461 --> 36:06.297
throw it to you.
Then you've got it there

36:06.329 --> 36:08.465
and becomes--it
becomes physical.

36:08.498 --> 36:10.534
It's just--just
a beautiful trick

36:10.568 --> 36:12.903
and really designed to be done

36:12.936 --> 36:16.373
this kind of way across
the ocean, electronically.

36:16.407 --> 36:18.943
Really wonderful.
And what we love about you

36:18.976 --> 36:22.579
is how really,
really careful you are.

36:22.612 --> 36:27.251
Every word, every gesture
is so carefully thought out,

36:27.284 --> 36:29.052
so carefully choreographed.

36:29.085 --> 36:32.255
You're watching every move,
doing every move,

36:32.289 --> 36:35.592
every word you say
exactly perfectly chosen.

36:35.626 --> 36:37.961
And it's a joy to watch you.

36:37.994 --> 36:39.963
We love having you
on this show.

36:39.996 --> 36:41.632
You fooled us last time.

36:41.666 --> 36:43.833
We don't think
you fooled us this time.

36:43.867 --> 36:45.936
I think I snuck
a few things in.

36:45.969 --> 36:47.637
I tried to be pretty subtle,

36:47.672 --> 36:49.373
'cause I don't want
to give it away on you,

36:49.407 --> 36:53.244
but don't think you fooled us,
but boy, we love you, Adrian.

36:53.277 --> 36:55.478
- Adrian, did they sneak in
enough words

36:55.512 --> 36:58.315
to let you know that they know
how you did your trick?

37:00.016 --> 37:02.686
- Of course, this was
for her--for the pleasure.

37:03.954 --> 37:05.523
- And you were
completely successful.

37:05.556 --> 37:06.891
Thank you.
- Well, thank you,

37:06.923 --> 37:10.228
Adrian Carratala.
- You're welcome.

37:10.260 --> 37:11.295
Thank you.

37:14.632 --> 37:17.068
- When "Fool Us" returns,
we hand the stage over

37:17.101 --> 37:18.568
to our headliners.

37:18.603 --> 37:21.172
See Penn and Teller perform
right after this.

37:21.204 --> 37:22.440
Stay close.

37:22.472 --> 37:26.844
♪ ♪

37:29.880 --> 37:32.916
[jazz music]

37:33.751 --> 37:35.018
- Penn and Teller love

37:35.052 --> 37:37.355
to ruffle the feathers
of the magic community

37:37.387 --> 37:39.657
by revealing
how tricks are done.

37:39.690 --> 37:42.193
Here to show the method
behind their magic,

37:42.226 --> 37:44.561
it's Penn and Teller.

37:47.431 --> 37:49.800
- When we first got the idea
for this show,

37:49.833 --> 37:52.235
we thought we will close
every show

37:52.269 --> 37:53.737
with a Penn and Teller trick.

37:53.771 --> 37:56.340
That would be a great idea,
and we had a lot of materials.

37:56.373 --> 37:59.543
We did live shows, so we pulled
stuff out of the live show,

37:59.577 --> 38:01.512
just did it
at the end of the TV show.

38:01.545 --> 38:03.047
We thought that would be great.

38:03.079 --> 38:05.983
But we never thought it would
run more than two seasons.

38:06.016 --> 38:09.487
So now we've done nine seasons,
over 100 of these closers,

38:09.519 --> 38:12.188
and we are plumb
out of material.

38:12.222 --> 38:13.757
We are tap city.

38:13.791 --> 38:15.192
So now we have
to come up with stuff.

38:15.226 --> 38:17.295
We can't just think
of what we'd like to do.

38:17.327 --> 38:19.697
We just need to come up
with stuff like crazy.

38:19.730 --> 38:22.166
So one technique we use
is to go to old tricks,

38:22.199 --> 38:24.501
not other people's,
but public domain,

38:24.534 --> 38:27.137
and try to do a Penn
and Teller version of those.

38:27.170 --> 38:28.806
So here's the trick.
We're gonna show you

38:28.838 --> 38:30.173
exactly how it's done.

38:30.206 --> 38:32.043
But first, we'll show you
what the trick is.

38:32.076 --> 38:34.744
It is the doughnut
on the ribbon trick.

38:34.778 --> 38:37.047
So go to your friend,
and you have them thread

38:37.081 --> 38:40.483
a doughnut onto a ribbon
and tell them to hold

38:40.518 --> 38:43.487
both ends of the ribbons
and never let go.

38:43.521 --> 38:46.724
Then you explain
that doughnuts have integrity,

38:46.757 --> 38:50.293
not just morally and ethically,
but also structurally.

38:50.327 --> 38:53.197
So if you rip a doughnut apart
to get it off the ribbon,

38:53.230 --> 38:54.965
you could not
put it back together.

38:54.998 --> 38:56.534
Then you show them a miracle.

38:56.567 --> 38:58.902
You put a napkin
over the doughnut,

38:58.936 --> 39:01.505
reach under, say magic words,
if you want,

39:01.539 --> 39:06.443
and then show them the doughnut
with complete integrity.

39:06.476 --> 39:08.211
Let them examine it.
It's a little sticky.

39:08.244 --> 39:10.213
Let them examine it
all they want

39:10.246 --> 39:12.550
because that is
a perfect doughnut

39:12.583 --> 39:14.085
that came off the ribbon.

39:14.117 --> 39:17.021
That is a miracle.

39:17.054 --> 39:21.324
Now, you can do that--you can
do that trick at home

39:21.358 --> 39:22.992
'cause we're going
to show you the secret.

39:23.027 --> 39:24.661
Now, here's the secret.

39:24.695 --> 39:27.998
You take the doughnut and you
have your friend thread it on.

39:28.798 --> 39:31.369
And then while you're
talking about them holding it

39:31.402 --> 39:33.204
and the integrity
of the doughnut,

39:33.237 --> 39:36.873
you sneak in another doughnut,
a duplicate.

39:36.907 --> 39:38.309
You hook it over
your little finger,

39:38.342 --> 39:41.077
and we'll show you
what you do without the napkin.

39:41.112 --> 39:42.813
With a napkin covering it,
you reach out

39:42.847 --> 39:45.181
and you really do rip
the doughnut apart.

39:45.750 --> 39:48.219
You show your friend
the duplicate,

39:48.251 --> 39:53.289
and meanwhile, you just eat
the evidence, just like that.

39:53.324 --> 39:54.657
So here's the trick you can do,

39:54.692 --> 39:56.427
but that's not
a Penn and Teller trick.

39:56.460 --> 39:58.528
That's not big enough for TV.

39:58.561 --> 40:01.565
We have to make it bigger
and more Penn and Teller.

40:01.599 --> 40:03.233
So this shape is a torus.

40:03.266 --> 40:04.969
The shape here,
like a doughnut.

40:05.001 --> 40:07.271
So we thought, what else has--
there you go, Georgie.

40:07.304 --> 40:08.639
It's a little sticky.
Be careful.

40:08.672 --> 40:10.474
What else has that shape?

40:10.507 --> 40:12.710
And the answer came back:
a tire.

40:12.742 --> 40:15.579
And a tire also
has the integrity

40:15.612 --> 40:19.048
because if you break the tire,
you can't put it back together.

40:19.083 --> 40:20.251
It pops.

40:20.284 --> 40:21.385
So here's the Penn
and Teller version.

40:21.418 --> 40:22.619
Come on out, Georgie.

40:22.652 --> 40:24.021
Here's the Penn
and Teller version.

40:24.054 --> 40:25.822
It's not a doughnut on a
ribbon.

40:25.856 --> 40:29.059
It is a tire on a rope.

40:29.092 --> 40:31.762
So you've got a solid rope,
just like the ribbon.

40:31.795 --> 40:36.400
And then Teller comes out
with the exact same napkin.

40:36.434 --> 40:38.001
Okay.
Now, you at watching home,

40:38.034 --> 40:40.103
forget all about
the doughnut trick.

40:40.137 --> 40:43.706
This is now the Penn and Teller
tire on the rope trick.

40:44.442 --> 40:48.411
Same exact method,
same exact way of doing it.

40:48.445 --> 40:50.114
Forget about
the doughnut trick.

40:50.146 --> 40:52.282
This is the Penn and Teller
tire on--

40:52.315 --> 40:54.717
[tire pops]
Tire on the rope trick.

40:54.751 --> 40:58.688
See, both ends of the rope
are being held,

40:58.722 --> 41:02.927
and the tire is completely
and utterly intact.

41:02.960 --> 41:04.795
So forget
about the doughnut trick.

41:04.829 --> 41:07.565
This is a brand--this is
a brand-new trick,

41:07.597 --> 41:11.202
the Penn and Teller
tire on the rope trick.

41:13.570 --> 41:15.672
- Oh, no.
Don't eat that.

41:15.706 --> 41:17.173
- It's good.
It's good eating.

41:17.208 --> 41:19.777
- Okay, well, Teller is full
and Penn looks tired.

41:19.809 --> 41:22.713
Seems like a great time to say
good night from Las Vegas,

41:22.746 --> 41:27.318
and we'll see you next time
for a new episode of "Fool Us."

41:27.351 --> 41:30.820
Aww.

41:30.855 --> 41:32.655
Aww, thank you.
[indistinct]
